### Method Parameters in C#

C# provides several ways to pass parameters to methods: value, reference, output, and params.

### Value Parameters (Default)

By default, arguments are passed by value - a copy is made:

```csharp
static void Increment(int x)
{
    x++;  // Only modifies the copy
}

int num = 5;
Increment(num);
Console.WriteLine(num);  // 5 (unchanged)
```

### Reference Parameters (ref)

Modifies the original variable using `ref`:

```csharp
static void Increment(ref int x)
{
    x++;  // Modifies the original
}

int num = 5;
Increment(ref num);
Console.WriteLine(num);  // 6
```

### Output Parameters (out)

Returns multiple values from a method:

```csharp
static void Divide(int a, int b, out int quotient, out int remainder)
{
    quotient = a / b;
    remainder = a % b;
}

Divide(10, 3, out int q, out int r);
Console.WriteLine($"{q} remainder {r}");  // 3 remainder 1
```

### ref vs out

| Aspect | ref | out |
|--------|-----|-----|
| Initialization | Must be initialized before passing | Need not be initialized |
| Method requirement | May read/write | Must assign before returning |
| Purpose | Modify existing value | Return extra values |

### Params (Variable-Length Arguments)

Accepts a variable number of arguments:

```csharp
static int Sum(params int[] numbers)
{
    int total = 0;
    foreach (int n in numbers)
        total += n;
    return total;
}

Console.WriteLine(Sum(1, 2, 3));        // 6
Console.WriteLine(Sum(1, 2, 3, 4, 5)); // 15
Console.WriteLine(Sum());              // 0
```

### In Parameters (C# 7.2+)

Read-only reference parameter (no copying, no modification):

```csharp
static void Display(in int value)
{
    // value = 10;  // Compile error - in is readonly
    Console.WriteLine(value);
}
```

### Parameter Combinations

```csharp
// Params must be the last parameter
static void Log(string format, params object[] args)
{
    Console.WriteLine(string.Format(format, args));
}
```

> **Key Point:** Use `ref` when you need to modify the caller's variable. Use `out` when a method returns multiple values. Use `params` for methods that accept a variable number of arguments (must be the last parameter). Prefer value parameters (pass by value) for immutability.

### ref Locals (C# 7+)

```csharp
int[] numbers = { 1, 2, 3 };
ref int refElement = ref numbers[0];
refElement = 100;  // numbers[0] is now 100
```

codeExample:
using System;

class Program
{
    static void Main()
    {
        // ref
        int x = 5;
        Increment(ref x);
        Console.WriteLine($"After ref increment: {x}");

        // out
        int.TryParse("123", out int parsed);
        Console.WriteLine($"Parsed: {parsed}");

        // params
        Console.WriteLine($"Sum: {Sum(10, 20, 30, 40)}");
        Console.WriteLine($"Sum (no args): {Sum()}");
    }

    static void Increment(ref int n) => n++;

    static int Sum(params int[] numbers)
    {
        int total = 0;
        foreach (var n in numbers) total += n;
        return total;
    }
}
